05046nam a22007935i 9780231511827DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2007    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315118277 a10.7312/zhan140582doi  a(DE-B1597)459460  a(OCoLC)1013937293  a(OCoLC)979574874  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0080002bisacsh  aEG 97002rvk1 aZhang, Guixing, eauthor.10aMy South Seas Sleeping Beauty :bA Tale of Memory and Longing /cGuixing Zhang. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModern Chinese Literature from Taiwan00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator's Preface / rJaffee, Valerie -- tPart 1 -- tPart 2 -- tPart 30 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMy South Seas Sleeping Beauty is a captivating coming-of-age tale set in the magical jungles of Borneo. Told through the vivid recollections of a Chinese-Malay youth, the novel recounts the life of Su Qi, a troubled, sensitive son of a wealthy family, and exemplifies the imaginative range of one of Taiwan's most innovative writers. "There were all sorts of stories about how my younger sister died," Su Qi begins, hinting at the power of memory to bend and refract truth. Yet whichever the real story may be, the fact is that the death of Su Qi's sister created an irrevocable rift in Su Qi's family, driving his father into the arms of aboriginal women and his mother into a world of her own invention. In an effort to escape the oppression of home, Su Qi loses himself in the surrounding jungle, full of Communist guerillas and strange tropical fauna. The jungle further blurs the line between fantasy and reality for Su Qi, until he meets Chunxi, the beautiful, frail daughter of his father's best friend. Chunxi is an oasis of kindness and honesty in an otherwise cruel and evasive world, but after a bizarre accident, Chunxi falls into a deep coma, and Su Qui flees to Taiwan. In college Su Qi meets Keyi, a vivacious siren who helps Su Qi forget not only his violent past but also the colorful tales of his youth. When a family member dies, however, Su Qi is pulled back to the jungles of Borneo where he begins to unravel the secrets of his family's past-a story stranger than any fairy tale-and learns that his cherished dream of awakening his beloved Chunxi may be more than just a fantasy. Influenced by the lyricism of William Faulkner and the magical realism of Gabriel Garcia Marquez, My South Seas Sleeping Beauty is a deeply evocative exploration of sexuality and identity and a masterful reworking of Chinese and Western myth. Valerie Jaffee's careful translation retains all the tone and detail of the original work and provides rare access to a new and exciting generation of Chinese writers born in Southeast Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aJaffee, Valerie.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/zhan14058423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231511827.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL